## 6. Best Practices & Common Pitfalls

### Best Practices

- **Use structured (JSON) logs** at the source — far easier than grok-parsing free text.
- **Define explicit mappings** and index templates; avoid uncontrolled dynamic mapping.
- **Use `keyword` for exact/aggregatable fields**, `text` for full-text search.
- **Right-size shards** (~10–50 GB); avoid oversharding.
- **Use ILM + data streams** to automate rollover, tiering, and deletion.
- **Bulk index** and tune `refresh_interval` for high ingest.
- **Enable security** (TLS, auth, RBAC) — never expose Elasticsearch openly.
- **Add a buffer (Kafka/Redis)** for high-volume resilience.
- **Set JVM heap ≤ 31 GB**, ~50% of RAM.
- **Drop noisy logs** (debug/healthchecks) early in the pipeline.
- **Monitor the stack itself** (cluster health, disk, heap).

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Consequence | Fix |
|---------|-------------|-----|
| Exposing ES on 9200 publicly | Data breach / ransom | Enable security, firewall, never expose |
| No mappings (dynamic only) | Mapping explosions, wrong types | Explicit mappings + templates |
| Oversharding | Wasted memory, slow cluster | Fewer, larger shards; ILM rollover |
| Heap > 31 GB | Loses compressed pointers, GC issues | Cap heap at ~31 GB |
| Parsing free text with fragile grok | Brittle pipelines | Emit structured JSON |
| No retention/ILM | Disk fills, cluster red | ILM with delete phase |
| Single-doc indexing at scale | Poor throughput | Use `_bulk` API |
| `text` field used for aggregations | Errors / fielddata blowup | Use `keyword` subfield |
| `vm.max_map_count` too low | ES won't start | `sysctl -w vm.max_map_count=262144` |
| No buffer at high volume | Log loss on spikes | Kafka/Redis buffer |

